# Project Standards

## Product definition

- Achilles is an **AI-driven trust-boundary vulnerability discovery tool** (`github.com/dpopsuev/achilles`) that learns from historical CVE data to detect vulnerability patterns in new code.
- Built entirely on the Origami agentic circuit framework (`github.com/dpopsuev/origami`).
- **Core approach:** (1) Build datasets from known CVEs in major projects (Linux kernel, RHEL, OCP). (2) Learn the trust-boundary patterns — code shapes, API misuse, boundary crossings — that historically led to vulnerabilities. (3) Detect those patterns in target codebases before they become CVEs.
- **Initial targets:** Red Hat's core products — RHEL and OCP — for dataset creation, calibration, and wet runs.

## Current state (PoC scaffolding)

The codebase currently implements a `govulncheck` wrapper (scan → classify → assess → report) as proof that Origami works for a second domain. This is scaffolding, not the product. The real circuit will emerge as the dataset and pattern-recognition layers are built.

## Development methodology

- Start every story with Gherkin acceptance criteria (Given / When / Then).
- Follow the **Red-Orange-Green-Yellow-Blue** cycle (see `rules/universal/testing-methodology.mdc`).
- Run `go build ./...` after every change.
- Zero imports from Asterisk or any other consumer tool — Achilles depends only on Origami.

## Architecture

- `main.go` — CLI entry point (Cobra), node/edge/extractor registration, graph walk.
- `types.go` — Domain types (Severity, ScanResult, Assessment, Finding).
- `extractors.go` — `GovulncheckExtractor`, `ClassifyExtractor` implementing `framework.Extractor`.
- `nodes.go` — Circuit nodes (scan, classify, assess, report) implementing `framework.Node`.
- `circuits/achilles.yaml` — Circuit DSL definition.

## Scope

- Achilles is the second Origami reference implementation, proving the framework works for any domain.
- Advanced Origami features (Adversarial Dialectic, Masks, Team Walk, Ouroboros) are available but not yet used.
